We get this life by faith, and become linked to Emmanuel ‚Äî‚Äô‚ÄôGod with us.‚Äô‚Äô If I have God for me, I am going to overcome. How do we gain this mighty power?... by faith. The next passage I want to call your attention to is Romans, chapter eleven, verse twenty: ‚Äò‚ÄôBecause of unbelief they were broken off; and thou standest by faith.‚Äô‚Äô The Jews were cut off on account of their unbelief: we were grafted in on account of our belief. Second Corinthians, chapter five, verse seven: ‚Äò‚ÄôFor we walk by faith, not by sight.‚Äô‚Äô The most faulty Christians I know are those who want to walk by sight. They want to see the end ‚Äî how a thing is going to come out. That isn‚Äôt walking by faith at all ‚Äî that is walking by sight. I think the characters that best represent this difference are Joseph and Jacob. Jacob was a man who walked with God by sight. You remember his vow at Bethel: ‚Äî ‚Äò‚ÄôIf God will be with me, and will keep me in this way that I go, and will give me bread to eat, and raiment to put on, so that I come again to my father‚Äôs house in peace; then shall the Lord be my God.‚Äô‚Äô And you remember how his heart revived when he saw the wagons Joseph sent him from Egypt. He sought after signs. He never could have gone through the temptations and trials that his son Joseph did. Joseph represents a higher type of Christian. He could walk in the dark. He could survive thirteen years of misfortune, in spite of his dreams, and then ascribe it all to the goodness and providence of God. Lot and Abraham are a good illustration. Lot turned away from Abraham and tented on the plains of Sodom. He got a good stretch of pasture land, but he had bad neighbors.
